### Key interfaces/types to define first

```ts
export type WorkspaceId = string;
export type RoomId = string;
export type MeetingId = string;
export type MeetingInstanceId = string;
export type ParticipantId = string;
export type UserId = string;

export type LiveRole =
  | "owner"
  | "host"
  | "co_host"
  | "presenter"
  | "moderator"
  | "participant"
  | "viewer";

export interface RoomPolicy {
  lobbyEnabled: boolean;
  allowGuestJoin: boolean;
  joinBeforeHost: boolean;
  mutedOnEntry: boolean;
  cameraOffOnEntry: boolean;
  chatMode: "open" | "host_only" | "moderated" | "disabled";
  recordingMode: "manual" | "auto_on_start" | "disabled";
  screenShareMode: "hosts_only" | "presenters" | "everyone";
}

export interface RoomSummary {
  id: RoomId;
  workspaceId: WorkspaceId;
  name: string;
  slug: string;
  roomType: "instant" | "scheduled" | "recurring" | "persistent";
  policy: RoomPolicy;
}

export interface MeetingInstanceSummary {
  id: MeetingInstanceId;
  roomId: RoomId;
  workspaceId: WorkspaceId;
  title: string;
  status: "scheduled" | "prejoin" | "live" | "ending" | "ended";
  startsAt: string;
  hostUserId: UserId | null;
}

export interface ParticipantState {
  participantId: ParticipantId;
  userId?: UserId;
  displayName: string;
  role: LiveRole;
  presence: "lobby" | "active" | "breakout" | "reconnecting" | "left";
  audio: "muted" | "unmuted" | "blocked";
  video: "off" | "on" | "blocked";
  handRaised: boolean;
  joinedAt?: string;
}

export interface RoomEventEnvelope<TType extends string, TPayload> {
  eventId: string;
  roomEventNumber: number;
  type: TType;
  meetingInstanceId: MeetingInstanceId;
  occurredAt: string;
  actorParticipantId?: ParticipantId;
  payload: TPayload;
}
```

Scaffold rule:

- define contracts before implementation
- keep provider-specific media fields out of core domain types

## 15. Risks and decisions

### Biggest technical risks

- Media provider maturity risk. Cloudflare RealtimeKit pricing docs state the product is still in beta as of January 13, 2026. If you depend on it, you must test recording, breakout, moderation, and session recovery thoroughly before committing.
- Overloading Workers with media-adjacent tasks. The control plane belongs at the edge; the media plane does not.
- Weak role semantics. If moderator, presenter, and co-host overlap too much, host UX collapses into confusion.
- Treating chat, attendance, and summaries as afterthoughts. Those are part of the product differentiator.
- Using eventual-consistency stores for live authorization. KV is not the authority for live room state.
- Building too much whiteboard/collaboration surface before core join and moderation are excellent.

### Decisions that must be locked early

- Primary media strategy: Cloudflare RealtimeKit now, or provider abstraction with fallback from day one.
- Primary database: PostgreSQL via Hyperdrive, or a more constrained Cloudflare-only metadata stack.
- Auth model: guest-friendly magic links plus passkeys, and whether enterprise SSO is MVP or V2.
- Cookie domain and subdomain auth sharing model.
- Role semantics and which actions moderators may perform.
- Recording retention and download policy.
- Whether persistent rooms are first-class in MVP. They should be.
- Whether viewer mode ships in MVP or V2.

### Tradeoffs

- Cloudflare-native control plane gives excellent latency and operational simplicity, but it does not eliminate the need for a proper media service.
- PostgreSQL is less pure Cloudflare than D1, but it is a stronger system of record for this product.
- Guest join without mandatory account creation improves adoption, but it increases abuse and moderation pressure.
- Persistent rooms improve recurring workflows, but they require stronger governance, policy inheritance, and audit discipline.
- One-click host controls improve speed, but destructive actions need confirmation thresholds and audit logging.

## Build This First

1. Create the monorepo workspace with `apps/web`, `apps/admin`, `apps/api-worker`, `apps/auth-worker`, `apps/realtime-worker`, `apps/gateway-worker`, `apps/media-worker`, and shared packages.
2. Define the core domain contracts in `packages/shared-types` for rooms, meetings, meeting instances, live roles, room policy, participants, and room events.
3. Stand up the PostgreSQL schema and migration set for workspaces, users, rooms, meetings, meeting instances, participants, permissions, recordings, attendance, templates, and audit logs.
4. Build `auth.opsuimeets.com` first: session cookies, magic-link flow, join-token issuance, and middleware for workspace-aware auth resolution.
5. Build `api.opsuimeets.com` CRUD for room creation, scheduled meetings, recurring meetings, join-token validation, and host policy retrieval.
6. Build `ws.opsuimeets.com` with a room-scoped Durable Object that handles connect, disconnect, participant presence, lobby state, role changes, and ordered room events.
7. Build the public gateway and prejoin flow on `opsuimeets.com` and `app.opsuimeets.com`, including join-by-link, display-name capture, device preview, and request-entry flow.
8. Build the live room shell with the top state strip, participant rail, and one-click host dashboard before adding advanced collaboration features.
9. Integrate the media adapter for WebRTC session join, mic/camera/screen share, and recording start/stop, keeping provider-specific code isolated behind `packages/media-adapter`.
10. Add attendance rollups, recording webhooks, analytics event writes, and the first post-meeting summary page so every meeting already produces operational output.

